item.title: Diy Thumb Joystick Rocker Gimbals
item.description:
English:

I desinged this thumb joystick for a flight RC controller i'm making.
It's designed arround the potenciometer RV09 5kohm 1/4 turn. Only 2 potenciometers and a 2mm rod is needed as axle between the Y axis roller and the suport. The X axis is suported by the potenciometer.
The Y axis suports are glued to the back using cyanoacrylate.
The stick can be bolted to de X roller using 1/8' o M3 bolts or just glue.

Español:

Diseñe este joystick para un controlador RC de vuelo que estoy haciendo.
Esta diseñado para usar el potenciómetro RV09 5kohm de 1/4 de vuelta.
Solo se necesitan 2 potenciómetros y una varilla de 2mm que hace de eje entre tambor del eje Y y el soporte. El eje X rota sobre el eje del potenciómetro.
Los soportes del eje Y se pegan a la parte del atrás usando cianoacrilato.
El mango se atornilla al tambor del eje X con un tornillo de 1/8 o M3 o se puede pegar.

item.title: Over the Mirror Handicap Placard Holder
item.description:
Today's cars have mirror stalks and wiring that prevent the Handicap Placards from looping over the back of the mirror.

This allows you to easily hang the placard onto the front of the mirror. It is easy on and easy off which lets you put up and remove the placard in much faster time than feeling around the back of the mirror.

Even though it is easy to use, you may leave it up on the mirror as it is narrow and does not distract much from looking at the mirror.

Important!
Use a high temp flexible filament like TPU as the car gets pretty warm inside and PLA will not stand up and will deform.
item.author: rdupre

item.title: V-Roller Bearing Press
item.description:
I had to change out my worn out V-Rollers on my printer, and it felt like a waste throwing out all the old ones with perfectly good bearings, so I designed a small bearing press to remove them for later projects. I printed at 100% infill for maximum durability, but I'm unsure if that's necessary.

Print both the inner and outer portions. Insert the V-roller in the outer section, then with the inner, use the short peg to center it in the V-roller. Insert the assembly into a vise or press, and push it out. There will be a pop (the center ring of the wheel breaking off), then it will come out relatively smooth. You may be able to use a hammer as well, but I haven't tried.

The bearings in the wheels are standard 625 bearings, which is pretty handy to have.

item.title: 1:25 reamer for installing Wittner geared cello pegs
item.description:
STL is one half of a reamer I used for enlarging holes to install geared pegs in cello. Firstly, wrap two printed halves in aluminum foil so they don't melt. Insert sand paper in between two halves then wrap around it them fully (cut at angle so it covers the dowel equally). Attach to a drill and sand away w/o much force. Not for a faint of heart. No guarantees it works.

For 14mm Wittner pegs, 1:25 taper
Best to use cloth backed sandpaper or for wet sanding as they are more flexible.

item.title: Bald Eagle
item.description:
These files are designed for the most part for laser cutting. But if you are not confused by the small size, you can also print them on a 3D printer.
  To increase the size, you can cut these models into pieces, print them separately and then connect them with glue.
  Download the files you need one at a time by clicking the "Upload" button each time. If you want to download all the files in one click, click here.
  STL files are ready for printing on a 3D printer with a maximum print area size of 210x200. If your table size is larger, you can easily scale it to fit your size. To make a large-sized version of metal, wood or plastic, as in the picture, you will need the help of a laser cutter. To do this, I added dfx and svg files.
  Wall mounting can be done using wall_mounting. It must be printed additionally and glued with glue to the main decor. Then fix it on the wall with nails or screws or use double-sided tape.
 To achieve the wow effect, you need to place an LED strip on the back of the decor.

item.title: Activated Carbon Filter
item.description:
Activated carbon filter to remove odors from your 3D printer, works with FDM and resin.

The printer needs to be enclosed as is small and does not have the capacity to filter an entire room.

Requirements

  1. You need to print one box (you can choose the design you prefer, but squares are easier to print than hexagons), one separator, one lid and four feets. I have used PETG for all the pieces and TPU for the feets.

  2. You will need a 60mm x 25mm computer fan, I have used this Noctua which is very quiet, you will also need a suitable power adapter for your fan. Keep in mind that the voltage should not exceed that required by your fan and if possible it is better that it be exactly the same. USB cables typically provide 5 volts unless otherwise specified.

  3. You will also need 8 computer fan screws. They are called that, really.

Consumables

To filter the air you will need activated carbon sheets about 5mm thick. You will need to cut them to be 15mm high and 26mm wide, you can put multiple pieces together to reach that 26mm. I use these that are designed for cat litter boxes. These filters are the only consumable, you will have to change them when the odors no longer disappear.

Assembly

  1. Screw the spacer to the fan on the side that the air enters, some fans have an indication of the air flow direction. The spacer has a small hole to pass the cable, make sure they match.

  2. Insert the fan and spacer inside the box in the same way as shown in the image. You may need to use something long like a screwdriver to insert it all the way. The box has a hole on the side for the fan cable to go through, make sure they match.

  3. Now screw the fan to the box with the other 4 screws you had left. You'll probably need to support the fan while you screw it in so it doesn't slip in, so use a long object to hold it in place, like a second screwdriver.

  4. Insert the activated carbon sheets into the box in such a way that they cover the internal walls of the box, make sure that they remain in the gap between the separator and the walls of the box and that they never enter the central hole of the separator where they are find the blades of your fan. The fan cable should be sticking out of the box in order to complete the next step.

  5. Now is a good time to glue your four legs to the lid. Once this is done, fold the cable through the hole in the box in one of the corners and then simply close the box by pressing the lid. Keep in mind that the cover has a small protrusion that you must fit into the hole through which the cable comes out, make sure they match.

  6. One of the four corners has a small tab so you can insert your fingernail to open the lid more easily.

item.title: Rat Rig V-Core 3 Carbon Fiber 2020 Mod
item.description:
--------------------------------------------WORK IN PROGRESS-------------------------------------------
26/01/2022 - All files created and tested in CAD, first part of assembly done and tested. Will be drilling holes for Linear Rail tomorrow (27/01/2022) and updating this page.

XY_Joiner Drill Template - Confirmed works
XY_Joiner Inserts - Confirmed works
XY_Joiner_Left Carbon2020 - Confirmed works
XY_Joiner_Right Carbon2020 - Confirmed works
Linear_Rail Drill Template - Unconfirmed

Carbon Fiber 2020 weight reduction mod for the Rat Rig V-Core 3.
Inspired by Vez3D on Youtube.

Parts and drilling templates to convert your V-Core 3 2020 aluminium extrusion to Carbon Fiber.

----PRINTED PARTS LIST----

1x - XY_Joiner Drill Template
1x - Linear_Rail Drill Template

2x - XY_Joiner Inserts
1x - XY_Joiner_Left Carbon2020
1x - XY_Joiner_Right Carbon2020

----HARDWARE LIST----

6x - 3030 M5 T Nuts
1x - 2020 Carbon Fiber Extrusion (18mm x 18mm Internal Diameter)

----NOTES----

Original XY_Joiner Left and Right from RatRig had to be slightly modified to increase the size of the 20.2mm x 20.2mm rectangle hole to 20.6mm x 20.6mm. This may depend on the supplier of your Carbon 2020 extrusion. You may be able to sand down the original Rat Rig ones.

3030 T Nuts are used in the insert instead of 2020 T Nuts simply because they are bigger and I thought they would be more rigid. Also thats all I had laying around.

----PRINT INSTRUCTIONS----

0.4 Line Width, 0.2 Layer Height, 4 Walls, 25% Gyroid Infil.
Print orientation in pictures.
Support required on the "Linear_Rail Drill Template" and may be required on the "XY_Joiner Inserts" and Rat Rig XY Joiner left and right parts.

----ASSEMBLY----

Cut down 2020 Carbon Fiber extrusion to 422mm, same length as original aluminium extrusion. (this is for 300x300x300 V-Core 3, adjust accordingly for larger V-Core 3)

Identify the flatest side of the Carbon Fiber extrusion and make sure this is facing up.

Place "XY_Joiner Drill Template" over the Carbon Fiber extrusion so its aligned with the left end. Make sure orientation arrow is pointing to the left end and the other arrow is pointing up to the top surface of Carbon Fiber.

Tripple check it's flat and flush with the end. Then drill all 3 holes using a 5mm drill bit. Go slow so you do not split the Carbon Fiber. Depending on what material you use to print the template, keep the drill as straight as possible so you do not melt the drill bit guide.

Remove the "XY_Joiner Drill Template" and repeat for the Right Side. Arrow pointing to the right end and the other arrow pointing up to the top surface of Carbon Fiber.

Insert the 6x "3030 M5 T Nuts" into the 2x "XY_Joiner Inserts". I used the spare ones provided by Rat Rig. They are a snug fit so you may need to use a screw driver or tool to push them in all the way. Check thread of nut is aligned with hole. The "XY_Joiner Inserts" are designed for 18mm x 18mm internal diameter. They are very snug so some sanding may be required.

Finally for the "Linear_Rail Drill Template" this may not work as intented depending on your linear rail. The mounting holes must be centred to the rail. For the 300x300x300 V-Core 3, the end mounting hole must be 12.5mm from the end on either side. If not you could offset the "Linear_Rail Drill Template" otherwise you may need to find another method.

Position the "Linear_Rail Drill Template" over the top surface of the Carbon Fiber extrusion with the arrow pointing to the left end. Make sure it is flush with the left end. Drill the holes you require with a 3mm drill bit. I started from the left most hole and then skipped every other one for less weight.

Remove and rotate the "Linear_Rail Drill Template" 180 degrees to the right side. Make sure arrow is pointing to the right end and its flush with the right end. Drill holes mirrored to the left side.

Once holes are all drilled you first need to attach the Linear Rail to the Carbon Fiber. I used a long pole with a small spanner attached to the end to hold the M3 Locking Nuts. Push the pole down the Carbon Fiber extrusion with the nut held in the spanner and position under the hole then screw in the bolt from the top through the Linear Rail and Carbon Fiber. Once the bolt is nice and tight I then removed the pole and spanner and repeat for rest.

When you have finished attaching the Linear Rail, you can then insert the "XY_Joiner Inserts" into either end. Make sure you put them in the right way round. Depending on how tight a fit they are, you should be able to remove them if need be by using the centre hole. Screw in a M2 bolt as far as you can and then use that to pull them out.

You should now be done and ready to mount to your printer!
